# Provenance note: Layer B canonical source — distinct from Layer A
# (owl-axiomatization.clif covering OWL constructs' canonical FOL semantics).
# Per arc/upstream-canonical/README.md two-layer framing:
#   - Layer A: what `SubClassOf`, `Transitive`, `InverseObjectProperties`
#     etc. *mean* in FOL (covered by owl-axiomatization.clif)
#   - Layer B: what BFO's `Continuant`, `Occurrent`, `part_of`, ternary
#     parthood, BFO Disjointness Map etc. *mean* in FOL (covered by THIS file)
# The two-layer discipline operationalizes per the ADR-010 banked principle
# generalization (Q-β refinement 2026-05-06): license-verification-at-
# vendoring-time discipline applies to all vendored canonical sources
# regardless of format. Phase 4 entry-cycle Q-4-C ratifies this Layer B
# vendoring under the same discipline.

# Attribution per upstream license. Same BFO-ontology/BFO repo as Layer A;
# same CC BY 4.0 LICENSE governs.
license: CC-BY-4.0
license-url: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/
attribution: |
  Basic Formal Ontology (BFO) Project.
  Primary contributors to the BFO 2020 CLIF axiomatization include Barry
  Smith, Fabian Neuhaus, Chris Mungall, and the BFO development community
  (per BFO repository commit history at https://github.com/BFO-ontology/BFO).
  Distributed under Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0).
  See https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ for the full license text.
  Source: https://github.com/BFO-ontology/BFO (LICENSE created 2022-04-19,
  commit 294fa4167f2e59784abb1e1abb9467f7de37b0cd; same LICENSE governs as
  owl-axiomatization.clif Layer A vendoring per `owl-axiomatization.clif.SOURCE`).
modifications-to-vendored-file: |
  None at vendoring. The file content is byte-stable upstream at the
  verified commit; OFBT does not modify the vendored bytes. Pass 2a
  vendoring confirms SHA-256 matches upstream content at master HEAD at
  verification time.
license-compatibility: |
  CC BY 4.0 is permissive and compatible with OFBT's MIT distribution model
  for the in-repo (GitHub) distribution context. CC BY 4.0 attribution +
  license link is satisfied by this sidecar's `attribution`, `license`, and
  `license-url` fields.

  Forks or downstream redistributors of OFBT that include this vendored file
  as part of their distributed artifact (e.g., via npm publish without
  excluding `arc/upstream-canonical/` from the package files list) inherit
  the CC BY 4.0 attribution + change-disclosure obligations. The vendoring
  discipline anticipates this by keeping the file in `arc/upstream-canonical/`
  (a development verification artifact path) rather than runtime paths.

  OFBT's `package.json` `files` field (set per ADR-010 Q-α architect-ratified
  developer item) excludes `arc/upstream-canonical/` from the npm package,
  bounding the CC BY 4.0 compliance scope to the GitHub repo. Fork authors
  who alter the `files` field to include this path inherit the CC BY 4.0
  obligations downstream.

  Formal legal review NOT performed at v0.1; the v0.2-trigger condition
  recorded in ADR-010 (distribution-model change for runtime ARC manifest
  loading) applies identically to Layer B vendoring. Phase 4 vendoring
  inherits the same banked principle.

